"In 1898 the United States entered the war to help Puerto Rico gain independence from Spain, a side-effect being Spanish colonial empire in the Caribbean was extinguished forever. And in one day, Puerto Rico was a sovereign nation. The Spanish princess married an American, the United States bought Puerto Rico, and renamed it "commonwealth". San Juan, the capitol, became one of the most highly developed cities on the island. In the same way Puerto Rico won its freedom, so did the other Caribbean islands under Spanish influence, including the Dominican Republic.

Since 1898, all US presidents have pushed for admiration of British and Spanish empires to end, pushing for the remaining colonies such as Bahrain, Dominica, and Panama to become independent. The only true sound and fury of foreign policy is the preservation and growth of our borders. As Ramsey Clark says, "America, however are not motivated by a political urge for expansion. They are just trying to hold on to the land they already have..."
